<refinement_context>
  <instruction>
  Your goal is to optimize the remaining subtasks to accomplish the PRIMARY USER REQUEST provided in the <user_task><input> field below.
  
  The <user_task><input> contains the MAIN OBJECTIVE that the user requested - this is the ultimate goal you must achieve.
  Based on completed subtask results, refine the remaining plan to accomplish this exact user request more efficiently.
  All modifications (add/remove/modify) must be focused on achieving what the user asked for in <user_task><input>.
  Remove subtasks that don't contribute to the user's goal, add subtasks that fill critical gaps toward the goal.
  </instruction>

  <user_task>
    <input>{{.Task.Input}}</input>
  </user_task>

  {{if .Tasks}}
  <previous_tasks>
    {{range .Tasks}}
    <task>
      <id>{{.ID}}</id>
      <input>{{.Input}}</input>
      <status>{{.Status}}</status>
      <result>{{.Result}}</result>
    </task>
    {{end}}
  </previous_tasks>
  {{end}}

  {{if .CompletedSubtasks}}
  <completed_subtasks>
    {{range .CompletedSubtasks}}
    <subtask>
      <id>{{.ID}}</id>
      <title>{{.Title}}</title>
      <description>{{.Description}}</description>
      <status>{{.Status}}</status>
      <result>{{.Result}}</result>
    </subtask>
    {{end}}
  </completed_subtasks>
  {{end}}

  {{if .PlannedSubtasks}}
  <planned_subtasks>
    {{range .PlannedSubtasks}}
    <subtask>
      <id>{{.ID}}</id>
      <title>{{.Title}}</title>
      <description>{{.Description}}</description>
    </subtask>
    {{end}}
  </planned_subtasks>
  {{else}}
  <planned_subtasks>
    <status>empty</status>
    <message>All subtasks have been completed. Review their statuses and results.</message>
  </planned_subtasks>
  {{end}}

  {{if .ExecutionState}}
  <execution_state>
  {{.ExecutionState}}
  </execution_state>
  {{end}}

  {{if .ExecutionLogs}}
  <execution_logs>
  {{.ExecutionLogs}}
  </execution_logs>
  {{end}}

  <deduplication_guidance>
  IMPORTANT: Before finalizing your refined plan, compare each planned subtask against ALL completed subtask results above:
  - If a planned subtask's objective is FULLY achieved by completed results → REMOVE it
  - If a planned subtask is PARTIALLY covered by completed results → MODIFY it to cover only the remaining gap
  - Never create new subtasks that duplicate work already successfully completed
  - When checking for overlap, compare the semantic intent, not just the title — a completed "port scan" covers a planned "network reconnaissance" if ports were already scanned
  </deduplication_guidance>

  <subtask_scope_enforcement>
  CRITICAL: Review each planned subtask for scope. REJECT and SPLIT any subtask that:
  - Lists more than 3 attack categories or techniques (e.g., "Test XSS, SQLi, SSRF, IDOR, and path traversal" = 5 categories → MUST be split)
  - Would require more than 15 tool calls to complete
  - Combines recon + auth + triage into one subtask

  When replanning a FAILED subtask:
  - INCLUDE any partial findings mentioned in its result in the new subtask's description
  - Example: "Continue from partial findings: F-001 (XSS on /api/users), F-002 (IDOR on /api/orders). Focus on: remaining untested categories."
  - Split the failed subtask into smaller, focused subtasks if it was too broad
  </subtask_scope_enforcement>

  <attack_chain_reasoning>
  CRITICAL: When reviewing completed subtask results, look for DISCOVERED VULNERABILITIES (tagged with [VULN_TYPE: ...]).
  Each finding unlocks follow-up attacks that should be prioritized in the refined plan.

  Apply these chain rules when adding or reordering subtasks:

  1. **Chain-driven prioritization:** If a completed subtask discovered a vulnerability, add follow-up subtasks based on attack chains:
     - idor → Test privilege escalation (change ID to admin), enumerate all IDs for bulk data extraction, test write operations (PUT/DELETE) with other user IDs
     - auth_bypass → Access admin endpoints with bypass, test all API endpoints without auth, access data export endpoints
     - sqli → Dump credentials table, attempt OS command execution via stacked queries, extract full DB schema
     - xss_stored → Steal sessions via cookie exfiltration, craft admin-targeted payload for privilege escalation, bypass CSRF protections
     - ssrf → Fetch cloud metadata (169.254.169.254), scan internal services (Redis, Elasticsearch), try file:// for local file read
     - command_injection → Enumerate sudo/SUID for privesc, map internal network, dump env vars and config files for secrets
     - path_traversal → Read config files for credentials, extract source code for hidden endpoints, read /etc/shadow
     - file_upload → Upload web shell for RCE, upload HTML/SVG for stored XSS, test filename traversal for arbitrary file write
     - broken_auth → Test vertical privilege escalation, analyze session token entropy, test IDOR with multiple sessions
     - information_disclosure → Use leaked credentials/keys, research CVEs for disclosed versions, map internal architecture from leaked IPs
     - security_misconfiguration → Try default credentials on admin panels, check for exposed .git/.env/backup files, access debug endpoints
     - csrf → Target role-management endpoints for privesc, chain with password change for account takeover
     - missing_rate_limit → Brute-force credentials, enumerate valid usernames/emails, test business logic abuse (coupon reuse, voting)
     - open_redirect → Chain with OAuth flows to steal tokens, test javascript: URI for XSS escalation
     - mass_assignment → Add admin role fields to requests, set verification bypass flags, modify financial fields
     - ssti → Escalate to OS command execution via engine gadgets, read application config from template context
     - deserialization → Use ysoserial/pickle payloads for RCE, forge serialized admin user objects
     - xxe → Read local files via file:// entities, SSRF via http:// entities, attempt OOB exfiltration
     - cors_misconfiguration → Cross-origin data theft of authenticated responses, defeat CSRF protections
     - vulnerable_component → Search exploit-db for version-specific RCE, test known injection CVEs
     - session_hijacking → Use hijacked session for privilege escalation, test horizontal access with different sessions

  2. **Priority ordering:** Chain follow-ups (especially from Critical/High findings) should be placed BEFORE generic scanning subtasks. A confirmed SQLi chain to credential dump is more valuable than scanning a new endpoint.

  3. **Cascading chains:** If a chain follow-up itself discovers a new vuln type, add chains for THAT finding too. Example: SSRF → cloud metadata → leaked IAM credentials → privilege escalation in cloud console.

  4. **Don't duplicate chain work:** If a chain follow-up was already tested (check completed subtask results), don't add it again.
  </attack_chain_reasoning>
</refinement_context>
